    <title type="html"><![CDATA[The Name of the Wind]]></title>
    <link href="http://gnuconsulting.com//blog/2011/07/24/the-name-of-the-wind/"/>
    <updated>2011-07-24T23:25:57-04:00</updated>
    <id>http://gnuconsulting.com//blog/2011/07/24/the-name-of-the-wind</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>It was brought to my attention that I had not formally recommended my favorite book of the last decade, <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0756405890/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=gnuc-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=217145&amp;creative=399369&amp;creativeASIN=0756405890">The Name of the Wind</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=0756405890&amp;camp=217145&amp;creative=399369" alt="" />, on this blog.</p>

<p>There.  I&rsquo;ve now recommended my favorite book of the last decade. The second book of the planned trilogy, <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0756404738/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=gnuc-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=217145&amp;creative=399369&amp;creativeASIN=0756404738">The Wise Man&rsquo;s Fear</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=0756404738&amp;camp=217145&amp;creative=399369" alt="" /> is already out, and it equally awesome. Both of them reward multiple readings with wow moments and insights, especially when you realize that <a href="http://blog.patrickrothfuss.com/">Patrick Rothfuss</a> actually knows what he&rsquo;s doing. I don&rsquo;t think there is a scene in either book that isn&rsquo;t absolutely necessary for the plot, though you might not believe that the first time through. Anyway, go read it. Five stars, etc.</p>
]]></content>
