    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Speaking of Neil Gaiman]]></title>
    <link href="http://gnuconsulting.com//blog/2009/01/26/speaking-of-neil-gaiman/"/>
    <updated>2009-01-26T20:57:17-05:00</updated>
    <id>http://gnuconsulting.com//blog/2009/01/26/speaking-of-neil-gaiman</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>While most of his work is not for kids (the <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1563890119?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=gnuc-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1563890119">Sandman</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=gnuc-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=1563890119" alt="" /> books are fairly intense, and <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0060558121?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=gnuc-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0060558121">American Gods</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=gnuc-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=0060558121" alt="" /> isn&rsquo;t much better), the books he does do for kids are often fantastic.  And this has been further confirmed by the fact that <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0060530928?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=gnuc-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0060530928">The Graveyard Book</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=gnuc-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=0060530928" alt="" /> has just won the <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/27/books/27newb.html?_r=1&amp;partner=permalink&amp;exprod=permalink">Newbery Medal</a>.  Congrats, <a href="http://journal.neilgaiman.com/">Neil</a>!</p>
]]></content>
